\f0\b\fs56 Candied Citrus Zest\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs44 \cf0 The key to making candied citrus zest is extracting all of the bitter flavor imparted by the pith (the white, inner part of the peel). Since it's nearly impossible to remove the pith completely, the best way to get the bitter out is blanching the zest three times, by dropping it into boiling water to release the bitterness, then shocking it with ice water to stop the cooking (and repeat, and repeat).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs52 \cf0 Ingredients
\fs56 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs44 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4 citrus fruits\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 cup granulated sugar\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 cup water\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 tablespoons light corn syrup\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs52 \cf0 Procedures
\f1\b0\fs40 \uc0\u8232 
\fs44 Set two pots of water (with 1 quart of water in each) to boil over high heat. By the time you\'92re ready to start blanching, the water will be ready.\uc0\u8232 Use a peeler and make long broad strokes from pole to pole of the fruit. Avoid digging into the pith, but don\'92t fret if you\'92ve taken a bit as you peel.\u8232 Chop the zest into thin strips if desired.\u8232 Set up an ice bath by filling a large bowl three quarters of the way with ice cubes and cold water. Set the bowl near the stove, along with a slotted spoon, spider, or small strainer.\u8232 When the water comes to a boil, add the zest to Pot #1 and allow it to simmer for 20 seconds. Remove the zest from the water, either by fishing it out with the spider or pouring it through a strainer into the sink. Rinse and refill Pot #1 with another quart of water, and return the pot to a boil.\u8232 Plunge the zest into the bath of ice water. It\'92s helpful to keep the strands inside the strainer in the bath to avoid having to pick the zest out of the ice.\u8232 Repeat steps 5 and 6, first using Pot #2, and then using the newly boiled water in Pot #1. When you\'92ve finished the third round of blanching, retire Pot #1.\u8232 When you\'92ve finished blanching in Pot #2, you can immediately set up for the final step: candying. Using the ratio of 1 cup fresh water to one cup sugar for every four fruits you\'92ve zested, combine sugar, corn syrup, and water in Pot #2 and bring it to a boil over high heat, stirring occasionally.\u8232 Once all of the sugar has dissolved and the syrup is bubbling, reduce the heat to a simmer (just a few steady bubbles, as opposed to a rolling boil) and add the blanched zest. Simmer for about twenty minutes, until the zest is completely translucent and curling along the edges. The syrup will become thicker and take on some color from the peel. Store the zest in the syrup and allow it to cool before using. Refrigerate in a sealed container.\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 }